args:
Hildegarde's rigidity clashes with the others'
desire to enjoy some Valentine's cheer.
The reason for her obstinacy turns out to stem
from a memory of her difficult childhood. With
the help of her friends, she rethinks her attitude
and tries to enjoy the special occasion.
Run this by me again—you DON'T want\nus to have a good time on Valentine's?
That is NOT what I'm saying!
Then why do you get in our faces\nwhenever we try to enjoy ourselves?!\nI declare you Captain Funbane!
Everybody calm the heck down already!
Is there gonna be a fight?
There will be if SHE keeps trying to muck\nup Valentine's with her gloom and doom!
I'm not TRYING to pour cold water on the\nproceedings; I merely want people to\nshow a modicum of restraint!
Oh, of course. Silly me. I'll just celebrate\nthe holiday by standing perfectly still\nand coughing occasionally. Will that do?
You may choose to be Captain Funbane,\nbut that doesn't mean the rest of us\nhave to join your un-merry crew!
I don't remember reading any Church\nprecepts that said, ＂Thou shalt not\nparty most hearty!＂
Ooookay! Maybe we should all\ntake five here, yeah?
We're friends, remember? So maybe we\nshould go cool off and then talk about\nthis once we've calmed down.
An adult knows when it's time to quit.
Whew! Looks like we escaped disaster\nfor the time being.
But seriously, Hildegarde, you probably\nshouldn't be such a stick in the mud.
If all you care about is protecting order,\nyou're going to ruin your friendships—\nand then you'll be in REAL trouble!
So let's try to have some fun, okay?
Oof... I'm REALLY not a fan of tense\nsituations like this...
Sooo on that note...I leave the rest to\nyou, {player_name}!
My actions to all of you have been\nmost inexcusable.
What's going on with you, Hildegarde?\nYou've been acting super weird lately.
Protecting order is doubtless an \nimportant charge. And yet...
Well, perhaps I've been taking more issue\nwith this Valentine's event than is strictly\nnecessary.
Because I haven't enjoyed such special\nevents for a very long time.
I don't understand why they are fun.
As you may know, I was separated\nfrom my parents at a young age and\nraised in an orphanage.
I know not what my parents'\ncircumstances are now...
But until I was sent to the orphanage,\nI was raised in a perfectly normal home.
We were a normal, stable family that\nenjoyed seasonal events just as\neveryone else did.
So whenever the orphanage would\ncelebrate a holiday, it would make\nme think about my family.
Those memories were so very painful\nthat I ended up trying to shut them out.
And rather than facing them, I focused on\nmaintaining structure and order instead.
So if you seek a reason for my actions,\nyou now have it.
...Hmm? What do I want to do now?
Look, just because big events used to\nmake you sad doesn't mean they ALWAYS\nhave to do that!
I mean, do you REALLY think events here\nare sad and lonely even though you're\nsurrounded by friends?
Well, I don't FEEL alone, I suppose.
However, I still can't make myself enjoy\nthem. In truth, I may just not know how.
Man, Hildegarde, this has to be a huge\nbummer for you. I'm really sorry.
But if you don't know how to have fun,\nlet us help you learn!
You don't need to think that hard about it;\nyou just do whatever sounds good.
And if you don't know what that is,\nwe'll help you find something.

I used to spend events locked away in
my room praying fervently until dawn.
Everyone chose to ignore me, which...
Well, I can't really blame them for that.
But things are different now. I have a\nfriend who accepts me as one of his\ncompanions and is truly concerned.
And with that being the case,\nperhaps I AM capable of change.
